\begin_layout Part
Class Notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th 
\series bold
moment 
\series default
is by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{I}t^{n}\mathrm{d}\mu(t)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Ij$
\end_inset

 is a subinterval of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The moment problem says that if we are given a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{n})$
\end_inset

 of real numbers, can we find a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}=\int_{I}t^{n}\mathrm{d}\mu(t).
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=[0,1]$
\end_inset

, then this is called the Hausdorff moment problem.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

, then this is called the Stieltjes moment problem.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=(-\infty,\infty)$
\end_inset

, then this is called the Hamburger moment problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us start with some intuition on how we can solve this problem.
 For a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, let us denote
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle f,\mu\rangle=\int_{I}f\mathrm{d}\mu\label{eq:innerproductfunctionmeasure}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In some sense, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:innerproductfunctionmeasure})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 behaves like an inner-product.
 Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 are different types of mathematical objects; one is a function and the
 other is a measure.
 So for all functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and measures 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Convex Cones
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 A set 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 is said to be a 
\series bold
convex cone 
\series default
if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
if 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in K$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y\in K$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha x\in K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a convex cone 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq V$
\end_inset

, if we have the additional axiom 
\begin_inset Formula $-K\cap K=\{0\}$
\end_inset

, then we can define a partial order on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 as follows: if 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in V$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leq_{K}y$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $y-x\in K$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq_{K}x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Thus it makes sense to call the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
positive 
\series default
elements with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq_{K}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extending Linear Functionals Which Satisfy Positivity Condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Marcel Extension Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be a convex cone.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $V=W+K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon W\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a linear functional such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K\cap W$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 is a linear functional such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{W}=\psi$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}(x)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V\backslash W$
\end_inset

.
 We will first show that we can extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 to a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon W+\mathbb{R}v\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W+\mathbb{R}v=\{w+\lambda v\mid w\in W\text{ and }\lambda\in\mathbb{R}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Define two sets
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\{x\in W\mid x+v\in K\}\quad\text{and}\quad B=\{y\in W\mid y-v\in K\}.
\]

\end_inset

We claim that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sup\{-\psi(x)\mid x\in A\}\leq\inf\{\psi(y)\mid y\in B\}.\label{eq:convexconeineq-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Then note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x+y & =(x+v)+(y-v)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

shows us that 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y\in K$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq\psi(x+y)\\
 & =\psi(x)+\psi(y)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $-\psi(x)\leq\psi(y)$
\end_inset

, and hence we have 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:convexconeineq-1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}(v)$
\end_inset

 to be any number between 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup\{-\psi(x)\mid x\in A\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf\{\psi(y)\mid y\in B\}$
\end_inset

 and we define we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon W+\mathbb{R}v\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{\psi}(w+\lambda v)=\psi(w)+\lambda\widetilde{\psi}(v)\label{eq:welldefinedpsitilde-1-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w+\lambda v\in W+\mathbb{R}v$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedpsitilde-1-1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined since 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent from 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedpsitilde-1-1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon W+\mathbb{R}v\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{W}=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\psi(x)\leq\widetilde{\psi}(v)\leq\psi(y)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B$
\end_inset

.
 The only thing left is to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the positivity condition.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w+\lambda v\in K\cap(W+\mathbb{R}v)$
\end_inset

.
 We consider the folloiwng cases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 1: 
\series default
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1/\lambda)w+v=(1/\lambda)(w+\lambda v)\in K
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\lambda)w\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq\lambda(\psi((1/\lambda)w)+\widetilde{\psi}(v))\\
 & =\psi(w)+\lambda\widetilde{\psi}(v)\\
 & =\widetilde{\psi}(w+\lambda v).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\series bold
Case 2: 
\series default
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda<0$
\end_inset

.
 Then note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(-1/\lambda)w-v=(-1/\lambda)(w+\lambda v)\in K
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1/\lambda)w\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq-\lambda(\psi((-1/\lambda)w)-\widetilde{\psi}(v))\\
 & =\psi(w)+\lambda\widetilde{\psi}(v)\\
 & =\widetilde{\psi}(w+\lambda v).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 3: 
\series default
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in K\cap W$
\end_inset

, and hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq\psi(w)\\
 & =\widetilde{\psi}(w).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the positivity condition is satisfied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now to extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 to all of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, we must appeal to Zorn's Lemma.
 More specifically, we define a partially ordered set 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},\leq)$
\end_inset

 as follows: the underlying set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}=\{\text{linear functionals }\psi'\colon W'\to\mathbb{R}\mid W'\supseteq W,\text{ }\psi'|_{W}=\psi\text{, and }\psi'(x)\geq0\text{ for all }x\in W'\cap K\}.
\]

\end_inset

A member of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is denoted by an ordered pair: 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi',W')$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{1},W_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{2},W_{2})$
\end_inset

 are two members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{1},W_{1})\leq(\psi_{2},W_{2})$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{2}\supseteq W_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}|_{W_{1}}=\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that every totally ordered subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},\leq)$
\end_inset

 has an upper bound.
 Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(\psi_{i},W_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is a totally ordered subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},\leq)$
\end_inset

.
 Then if we set 
\begin_inset Formula $W'=\bigcup_{i\in I}W_{i}$
\end_inset

 and if we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'\colon W\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 as follows: if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'(x)=\psi_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then it is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi',W')$
\end_inset

 is a member of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 which is an upper bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(\psi_{i},W_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore by Zorn's Lemma, there exists a 
\emph on
maximal 
\emph default
element in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},\leq)$
\end_inset

.
 This maximal element 
\emph on
must 
\emph default
be defined on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, otherwise we can extend it to a larger subspace as shown above.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hausdorff Moment Problem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=C[0,1]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=P[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}=\{\text{nonnegative continuous functions on }[0,1]\}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 we write it as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x)=b_{n}x^{n}+b_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+b_{1}x+b_{0},
\]

\end_inset

and we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(p)=b_{n}a_{n}+b_{n-1}a_{n-1}+\cdots+b_{1}a_{1}+b_{0}a_{0}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x^{i})=a_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This is clearly a linear functional on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 The first crucial step is to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{P}\cap\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 We'll need to use the following theorem of Bernstein:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (S.
 Bernstein) A polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is non-negative on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 if and only if it can be represented as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x)=A_{0}x^{n}+A_{1}x^{n-1}(1-x)+A_{2}x^{n-2}(1-x)^{2}+\cdots+A_{n-1}x(1-x)^{n-1}+A_{n}(1-x)^{n}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0},A_{1},\dots,A_{n}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x^{i}(1-x)^{j})\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\geq0$
\end_inset

 then by the previous theorem of Bernstein, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{P}\cap\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 It turns out that this is a sufficient condition too.
 We write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{i}(1-x)^{j}=x^{i}\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}x^{k}=\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}x^{i+k}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi(x^{i}(1-x)^{j}) & =\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}\psi(x^{i+k})\\
 & =\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}a_{i+k}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So we need to impose the condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}a_{i+k}\geq0
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Under this condition, we have that all conditions of the Marcel Riesz extension
 theorem are satisfied, namely we need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=\mathcal{P}+\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 However this is clear: if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is bounded, say 
\begin_inset Formula $f\leq M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=(f-M)+M,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f-M\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 So applying the Marcel Riesz extension theorem, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon\mathcal{M}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}(p)=\psi(p)$
\end_inset

 for any polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}(f)\geq0$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
 The final important ingredient is the Riesz Representation Theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Riesz Representation Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Riesz Representation Theorem) For any linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon C[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(f)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\geq0$
\end_inset

, there exists a unique finite (positive) measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(f)=\int_{0}^{1}f\mathrm{d}\mu
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Uniqueness is clear.
 Let's prove existence.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B[0,1]$
\end_inset

 be the space of all bounded functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=B[0,1]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=C[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}=\{\text{nonnegative bounded functions}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone.
 We also have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=\mathcal{P}+\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 by the same reason as before.
 Indeed, for any bounded function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 there exists a continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\leq f$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=(f-g)+g
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f-g\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 We also know 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(f)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{P}\cap\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 So by the Marcel Riesz extension theorem, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}\colon B[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}|_{C[0,1]}=\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}|_{\mathcal{P}}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Now we define a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}[0,1]$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu(E)=\widetilde{\ell}(1_{E})
\]

\end_inset

for each 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{B}[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 We next show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is a measure.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(E_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of pairwise disjoint sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}\right) & =\widetilde{\ell}\left(1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\\
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Observe
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{n}-f,f-f_{n}\leq|f_{n}-f|\leq\|f_{n}-f\|_{\mathrm{sup}}
\]

\end_inset

 By the positivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\ell}(f_{n}-f),\widetilde{\ell}(f-f_{n})\leq\widetilde{\ell}(\|f_{n}-f\|_{\mathrm{sup}}).
\]

\end_inset

Equivalently,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\widetilde{\ell}(f_{n}-f)|\leq\widetilde{\ell}(\|f_{n}-f\|_{\mathrm{sup}})=\|f_{n}-f\|_{\mathrm{sup}}\widetilde{\ell}(1).
\]

\end_inset

Therefore if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 uniformly.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}$
\end_inset

 is continuous with respect to the sup norm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now if 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 is an increasing sequence which converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 uniformly (Dini's Theorem).
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 is increasing and converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(f_{n})\to\widetilde{\ell}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{N}E_{n}}\nnearrow1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}}.
\]

\end_inset

It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}\right) & =\widetilde{\ell}\left(1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\widetilde{\ell}\left(1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{N}E_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\widetilde{\ell}\left(\sum_{n=1}^{N}1_{E_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\widetilde{\ell}(E_{n})\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\mu(E_{n})\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mu(E_{n}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is a Borel measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 It is finite since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu([0,1])=\widetilde{\ell}(1_{[0,1]})<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an increasing sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi_{n})$
\end_inset

 of simple functions which converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Then by MCT we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu\to\int_{0}^{1}f\mathrm{d}\mu.
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}1_{A_{k}}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi\mathrm{d}\mu & =\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}\mu(A_{k})\\
 & =\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}\widetilde{\ell}(1_{A_{k}})\\
 & =\widetilde{\ell}\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}1_{A_{k}}\right)\\
 & =\widetilde{\ell}(\varphi).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(\varphi_{n})\to\widetilde{\ell}(f)=\ell(f)$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu\to\ell(f)
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(f)=\int f\mathrm{d}\mu$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another formulation of the Riesz Representation Theorem is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Riesz Representation Theorem) For any bounded (with respect to the supremum
 norm) linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon C[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(f)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\geq0$
\end_inset

, there exists a unique finite (signed) measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(f)=\int_{0}^{1}f\mathrm{d}\mu.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And a more general version of the Riesz Representation Theorem is given
 by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Kakutani general version of the Riesz Representation Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a compact Hausdorff topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C(X)$
\end_inset

 be the Banach space of all continuous functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 equipped with the supremum norm:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|f\|_{\infty}=\sup_{x\in X}|f(x)|.
\]

\end_inset

For any bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon C(X)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique Borel regular measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(f)=\int_{X}f\mathrm{d}\mu.
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

